---
title: Chicken Katsu with Roasted Green Beans & Ginger Rice
description: Crispy chicken may just be the world’s most beloved food. Hear us out: Southern-fried, milanese, schnitzel, kiev—all types of crispy chicken from all corners of the world. True to form, this Japanese-style rendition is comforting and delicious. Here, chicken is pounded thin, coated in panko and cornstarch, then flash-fried to light and crunchy perfection. On the side is a classic katsu dipping sauce plus tender roasted green beans and ginger-scented rice. The results, unsurprisingly, are impressively tasty (and crispy as all get-out).
image: https://img.hellofresh.com/f_auto,fl_lossy,h_640,q_auto,w_1200/hellofresh_s3/image/60d333de2d8a3c2d6548d6a6-610fbe40.jpg
pdf: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipecards/card/chicken-katsu-60d333de2d8a3c2d6548d6a6-0905e866.pdf
author: Michelle Doll Olson
source: https://www.hellofresh.com/recipes/chicken-katsu-60d333de2d8a3c2d6548d6a6
servings: 2
time required: 30 minutes
cuisine: Asian
course: main course
nutrition:
  calories: 730 kcal
  fat: 33 g
  saturated fat: 9 g
  carbohydrates: 71 g
  sugar: 12 g
  protein: 33 g
  fiber: 3 g
  sodium: 970 mg
---

Adjust rack to top position and preheat oven to 425 degrees. Wash and dry produce.

Peel and mince or grate @ginger{1%thumb}. 

Heat a drizzle of oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add ginger; cook,
stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @jasmine rice{1/2%cup} and @water{3/4%cup}. Bring to a boil; cover and
reduce heat to low. Cook until rice is tender, ~{15-18%minutes}. Keep covered
off heat until ready to serve.

While rice cooks, toss @green beans{6%ounce} on a #baking sheet{} with a
drizzle of oil; season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Roast on top rack until browned and tender, ~{12-15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, pat @chicken cutlets{10%ounce} dry with #paper towels{}. Place between
two pieces of #plastic wrap{} and pound with a #mallet{} or #heavy-bottomed pan{}
until ½ inch thick. Season all over with @garlic powder{1%tsp}, @salt{}, and
@pepper{}.

On a #shallow dish{}, combine @panko breadcrumbs{1/2%cup}, @cornstarch{1%tbsp},
and @salt{1/2%tsp}. Brush a thin layer of @sour cream{2%tbsp} onto both sides
of chicken (you may not use all the sour cream). Working one piece at a time,
press chicken into panko mixture, coating all over.

Heat a 1⁄3-inch layer of @vegetable oil{2%tsp} in a #large nonstick pan{} over
medium-high heat. Once oil is hot enough that a pinch of panko sizzles when
added to the pan, add chicken. Cook until panko is golden brown and chicken is
cooked through, ~{2-3%minutes} per side.

> For 4 servings, cook in batches. Thinner pieces will cook faster.

Transfer to a paper-towel-lined plate.

Place @katsu sauce{4%tbsp} in a #small microwave-safe bowl{}; microwave until
warm, ~{20%seconds}.

Fluff rice with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tbsp} and season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}.

Divide rice, chicken, and green beans between plates. Drizzle chicken with
katsu sauce to taste (or serve on the side for dipping). Sprinkle chicken and
green beans with as many @sesame seeds{1%tbsp} as you like and serve.